Merge pull request #2 from isagalaev/master

Python refactoring

Store piece configuration directly.

- The set of available configurations is moved up to the class
  level, as it is constant across instances
- The instance keeps the configuration directly in self.data
  instead of getting it indirectly with an index.
- Also, `random.choice` is simpler than messing with indices.

Using "all" in position_ok.

- Conditions are reverted to use shorter 0 <= x < PLAYFIELD_H syntax
- "all" is used to check conditions for all cells of a piece.

Useful TetrisPiece constructor.

Unlike C++, Python has no problem with having useful object
constructors that do whatever initialization needed. So calling a
trivial constructor and setting up attributes one by one after that
is an anti-pattern.

Also, there's no point in having setters and getters for plain
data fields.

Simpler TetrisController.move and piece position.

Instead of doing "move - check position - unmove - move again if
ok" it's easier to teach a TetrisPiece to return its cells at the
new position, check that and then move if ok.

Also, replacing separate x, y, z attributes with a tuple reduces a
few lines of code.

Moving run() out of TetrisInputProcessor.

This is going to be the main theme of the refactoring. Since it's
not Java, there's no need to define everything as classes. It makes
Python code less readable with all those millions of `self.` and it
encourages usage of class attributes instead of simple local vars.
A rule of thumb is: if you're creating an single instance of a class
that lives through the whole program lifetime it shouldn't be a
class. Same goes for classes with a single public method.

Here's what's changed here:

- run() has been moved out of the class and lost its `self`
- instead run() creates an instance of the TetrisInputProcessor,
  which in turn will probably go away in the future as having a
  whole class to hold a single var looks like an overkill.

Context managers for terminal setup/restore.

A context manager is a common idiom to define blocks with
guaranteed resource release. They can be defined as classes but
there's a nicer syntax using contextlib.contextmanager that lets
you define a function with a single `yield` in the middle, so you
can acquire resources before that and release them after.

Also after extracting those it seems that the thing with termios
attrs is not needed as you don't set anything before doing the work,
so there's probably nothing to restore. But I'm not the judge here.

Moving executable code under '__main__'.

It is a common idiom for keeping executable part of code from
executing if this file is imported as a module somewhere.

Пришлось много порефакторить. Теперь укаждого уровня была своя FigureQueue, поскольку теперь рандомайзер с изменением вероятности - ее свойство. А в TetrisGame инджектится Levels. Тогда как раньше FigureQueue была одна для всех и инджектилась во все уровни и TetrisGame. Так же пришлось написать ряд рандомизаторов, чтобы иметь возможность менять вероятность появления последней фигурки.

Теперь на админке можно изменить тип игры из числа описанных в пакете levels.

Классы грузятся динамически из пакета levels. Сервис настроек не защищен от многопоточной работы с ним - надо защитить. Новые настройки вступят в силу только для заново зарегистрированных игроков.

Изменил уровни сложности + вывел на боард юзера информацию о том, что надо для перехода.

Сделал так, чтобы можно было менять уровни сложности игры. Теперь уровней сложности три.
- Тот, что был раньше - HardLevels - переход по снятию 4х строк.
- Легкий, в котором включается не более одной фигурки и переход осуществляется по снятию 10 строк: EasyLevels.
- И суперсложная игра: AllFigureLevels, где все фигурки сразу.

Сделал возможным переход на следующий уровень по общему количеству снятых строк.

Вывел на экран пользователя (board) дополнительную информацию: текущий уровень, количество снятых линий и критерий перехода на следующий уровень.
Поменял read lock на write lock

Главная страничка + на форме регистрации заполнен IP пользователя + удаления пользователя
Добалена главная страничка, на которой можно выбрать список действий для пользователя (как зарегистрированного уже, так и нового). Для зарегистрированного пользователя возможно: перейти на хелп, зарегистрироваться, посмотреть доску почета. Для незарегистрированного: хелп, посмотреть свою доску, посмотреть доску почета, выйти из игры.

Так же на форме регистрации вводится IP пользователя автоматически. Дважды зарегистрироваться с одного IP невозможно. Для зарегистрированного пользователя можно выйти из игры и тоглда лишь зарегистрироваться снова.
Добавил админку на которой можно приостановить игру для ретроспективки и возобновить обратно.

Выделил поясняющие константы в Player Scores.

Теперь каждый игрок зарегистрировавшийся после всех получает минимальное количество очков (если есть отрицательный счет), либо 0, если другие игроки "в плюсах". Есть рсик, что у играющего хуже всего (минимальный отрицательный счет) стакан уже может быть заполнен под завязку, и тогда новобранец будет на предпоследнем места сразу после переполнения стакана у соперника - решили оставить как есть.

ISSUE-2: VMEmulator built-in classes not useable from command line

The use of built-in classes is now controlled by the environment
variable N2T_VM_USE_BUILTINS.

If set to "yes" (case insesitive), the built-in classes will be
used without prompting.

If set to "no", the built-in classes won't be used (again, no
prompting).

In any other case, we'll fallback to the previous behaviour. That
is, prompt for GUI and reject for CLI.

Fixed questionable use of generic Exception

Don't throw generic Exception @jakeryang . Always be specific. In this case, I found the IllegalStateException to be most appropriate, which is also nice because it is unchecked, and doesn't need to tag every method in the call chain with "throws Exception". The other exception that was coming up was FileNotFound, but this is better handled by a try-catch in the method itself that exits immediately on failure.

More Novelty Work: Revealed Problem

#393 There is not a method that returns an array of the individual room novelties before calculating the average using a utility method.

However, I noticed that the average changed slightly each time, and this is because the room values change each time. This is a problem that needs to be fixed.

Removed "neighbor" concept from Novelty

#393 The calculation was getting neighboring rooms in terms of dungeon location, but the novelty concept is based on neighbors in characterization space.

However, to make things simple, I now just compute the novelty with respect to the whole list of other rooms.

So, instead, I'm now just retrieving the appropriate libraries through Maven.

MarioGAN can train new models now

The PyTorch compatibility changes I made allowed me to load previously trained models, but prevented me from training new ones. These changes allow new models to be trained. I also incorporated some code from the Dagstuhl branch that was missing for some reason ... specifically, code that would allow me to specify which json file to train with.

In fact, I also added the json files containing some Mario level information (surprisingly missing).

Here is a command to train a GAN for a short period of time as a quick test:
```
python main.py --niter 50 --nz 32 --problem 0 --json underground.json --experiment samples-50-underground-32
```

#283 MarioGAN works in Windows now!

This is because the latest version of Pytorch finally works in Windows
10. However, apparently PyTorch disallowed the use of "." in model names
a couple of versions ago, which means that the models that Vanessa and
Sebastian trained are deprecated.

In order to deal with this, some fixes had to be made to the code. First
the names in the models had all "." replaced with ":". Then, when the
models are loaded, the OrderedDict that represents the saved model has
to have its keys changed. More accurately, a new OrderedDict is made
with values in the same order, but with different (valid) key names.

Created OldToNewGhostIntermediaryController. As of right now, it takes a SharedNNGhosts<T> as its constructor. This is given to it in the only place it is constructed, MsPacManTask. The idea behind this class is that all of the decision making logic will be performed in this class. It contains four ZombieControllers and a MASController  made up of those four ZombieControllers. This class will set the moves of each of the zombies (one per ghost). When the MASController calls the getMove method, it will return those moves given to the Zombies by this class.

Refactored further to make most methods static

#193 @friedmaa I refactored the class further. I haven't tested it, but
everything that worked before should still work. This change makes most
of the important methods in the class static. The benefit of this
approach is that we will be able to call these methods from outside of
this class without the need to re-write or copy code. However, the
downside is the massive number of method parameters that now have to be
passed around in most cases.

Refactored UT2004Task to split out evaluation of multiple genotypes

All of the old evolution batch files should work with this code. It
behaves the same as the old code if you are only evaluating one agent at
a time. However, with the code like this, it should be easier to get
coevolution and other tasks working. @friedmaa  #193

Commented ActivationFunctionMutationTest, edited the test #110

The original test was asserting that the two lists of activation functions would be different. However, it is possible that the mutated function in the mutated genome statys the same. This is because when a activation function is mutated, a new function is chosen randomly from the list of possible functions. The original function has a chance of being chosen. The new test asserts that there is at most one difference between the two genomes to account for the instances where the mutation does not change the genome.

Rather than strictly scaling input and target values based on the maximums, I am now scaling them by dividing by the variance. Supervised learning for regression problems from CSV file

#74 This is the initial commit to allow MMNEAT to train a model for a supervised learning problem using data from a CSV file. It seems to work, in the sense that it loads the data and runs evolution in a seemingly correct way, but the current result is bad (which is actually somewhat expected ...). However, there are ways to improve it. For starters, the input and output values are currently not scaled in anyway, so the fact that I am using tanh activation functions would make it impossible to solve these problems currently. I also wonder if the MSE calculation is correct ... I'll need to look into it.

For now, the task runs, there is a default CSV file to test it with (contains made up data for a simple polynomial) and a batch file that runs the experiment.

#9 Image caching

All interactive evolution interfaces now cache user-selected images so that they do not need to be recomputed in the next generation. This is primarily beneficial for the style breeder. It will be used in the other cases, though I don't think any speed-up is noticable in those cases.

#9 Don't recompute content features

In the Python Neural Style Algorithm, I was able to move some code around to avoid recomputing the VGG features for the content image over and over. Since the image is constant, and only the style images change, this provides a small savings.

The pause when loading new images is still noticable, but this change is an improvement.

Save individual frames of 3D animations

To actually save the frames in a large size, I hard coded the cube size to be larger. That change is not in this commit ... I need to introduce it in a general way, if I ever use this code again.

Save frames of 2D animation

This is unrealted to the neural style branch. It loads a network for 2D animations and saves high quality version of each frame.

#33 #24 Wider network test

The process width is now 8. However, the depth could not be increased: 4
is the maximum process depth allowed by a convolutional net in Tetris
that uses a kernal of 3 by 3 because the input width has shrunk so much
by the time it reaches the 4th layer (moving upwards).

This can be fixed by using zero padding, or allowing different layer
configurations at each level.

#33 Lots of cahnges to make DL4J network same as HyperNEAT network: WORKS!

The Unit test for TensorNetworkFromHyperNEATSpecification actually
works! This means that the HyperNEAT substrate specification for Tetris
is correctly decoded to produce a DL4J network, and then each weight
from the substrate network is correctly copied over to the DL4J network.

The only small problem left is that it only works if the substrate
network uses the ReLU activation function for both the hidden neurons
and the output. The output should actually be tanh or a regular sigmoid,
but my HyperNEAT networks don't have a way of specifying different
activation functions for different layers yet.

However, I did make a related change: there is now an option to make the
input neurons use the ID activation function, which is actually a
standard convention that I have ignored for years.

Other changed include: swapping of substrate width and height when
defining input shape for DL4J, and deletion of an unnecessary method in
TWEANN that had actually been replaced by one in ActivationFunctions.

#27 Changes MAP Elites code a lot

After re-reading the innovation engines paper, I made several changes to make my approach more like thiers. Primarily, a genome can be stored in many bins now, and it does not have to be stored in the bin which corresponds to its best score. Even if a genome's best score corresponds to one particular bin, it may also be better than the current elite in another bin.

This definitely makes sense for Innovation Engines, but I fear it will make MAP Elites different to use in other domains in the future.

Also, the ImageNet being used now is VGG19 instead of VGG16

#25 Model loading works for VizDoom

Thanks to the help I got here
(https://github.com/deeplearning4j/rl4j/issues/61#issuecomment-327925186)
I was able to fix the network/model loading. The problem is that the
play method needs to take in a HistoryProcessor along with the MDP in
order to know how to properly decode the game state.

I'm not certain of this, but thinking back to the breakthough paper
about DQN in VizDoom I think that they fed in 4 frames of screen
information at a time, and this might be what the HistoryProcessor is
telling the DQN to do here, since the HistoryProcessor.Configuration has
a History length of 4.

#15 Code now allows all weights in receptive field for one feature to be the same

Originally, I was going to completely remove two of the CPPN inputs (for
target neuron coordinate) to make this work, but that ended up causing
problems. This is because, even in a network that is convolutional,
there will still be some fully connected components ... for example,
connecting the final processing layers to the output(s). In order to
define these links, the CPPN needs to have inputs for both source and
target neurons. However, when defining links in the convolutional
portions, the extra inputs are 0.

Also added a batch file to test all of this.

#455 Evolved WPC?

Right now, I think that Othello-HNStaticWPC05Second.bat is the most
appropriate batch file to use for SCOPE poster purposes, but this new
batch file tries one more approach. The name says WPC, but technically
HyperNEAT is still being used, but to evolve a "network" with only an
input and output layer. This is thus equivalent to a weighted piece
counter, since each link weight is the piece weight (accounting for the
bias as well). However, we should also have the benefit of geometric
awareness from HyperNEAT. Let's see how this works.

#455 How good is random play?

I tried making a unit test that pitted the random player against the
WPC, assuming that the WPC would always win. Naturallly, there must be
some chance of randomly picking only good moves, but I assumed the odds
would be so low as to not matter. I was wrong. I then put some code in
the board game post benchmark (it is commented out) that runs the random
player against the WPC many times (however many trials are specified)
and found out that the random player wins about 16% against the WPC.

If this is really true, it might explain some of the weirdness that
introducing non-deterministic play has caused, but I think it is more
likely that this indicates some kind of error, perhaps in how tree
search works. I'll need to look into it some more.

#455 Small random move percent

This batch file has a small random move percent (5%) and a slightly
larger population. However, there is only 1 trial. As a result, there
are always agents that win (highest fitness) but the average of the
population does not go up ... it is flat. It makes me wonder if the
random move percent affects both players (evolved and WPC) in such a
weird way that it causes problems.

Need to check the literature for other approaches to evolving in board
games ... maybe also consider confining random moves to the start of the
game match? Instead of having random moves instead of minimax, perhaps
start each game with a given number of random moves.

#455 Investigating minimaxRandomRate

Evolving with minimaxRandomRate = 0.0 allows evolution to beat the WPC.
There is still a bit of randomness from argmax tie breaks, but the
evolved agent scores clearly go up and hit a ceiling.

In contrast, changing minimaxRandomRate to 0.05 causes massive problems.

simplify this code as much as possible, so I've removed some suspicious
code, and also added batch files for testing.

Fixed OthelloPieceFitness

@DarwinJohnson
This fitness function was incorrectly adding up the piece differences
across every step of the game, but what I meant for it to compute was
the final piece difference at the end of the game only. Research has
shown that good Othello play often depends on having fewer pieces in the
mid game, only to come back with a surprise win at the end. Only the
final piece difference matters, while the piece difference in the middle
of the game is misleading.

#395 Able to specify Hall Of Fame Opponents

Created several Parameters meant to specify which Hall Of Fame Opponents
to play against. hallOfFameSingleRandomChamp causes the eval to be
against a single Champion chosen at random. hallOfFameXRandomChamps
selects a total of X random Champions, where X is equal to
hallOfFameNumChamps. hallOfFameYPastGens chooses Champions from the past
Y Generations, where Y is equal to hallOfFamePastGens.
It's possible to have both XRandomChamps and YPastGens set to true, or
to have only one or the other set to true. In addition, the number of
Champions chosen or the number of past Generations to choose from can be
changes with the parameters hallOfFameNumChamps or hallOfFamePastGens.

#320 Not actually a bug

I believe I've confirmed that the issue with the states you are printing
out is not actually a bug. As I indicated, several evaluations happen at
a time in batches. This is because the MLPSMCTS algorithm (and all tree
search algorithms really) start from the current state, but then
progress through the game tree to evaluate several possible future
states. The agent wants to pick the action that will most likely lead to
a future state that is highly valued, and also likely to happen (it is
not easy for the opponent to avoid the state).

I added a MiscUtil wait that you can use to view one batch of state
print-outs at a time.

@DarwinJohnson I found a ton of errors and problems and fixed most of
them. I've created some issues associated with issues I've found and
simply fixed others.

I believe that #409 is ok now, but I want you to do some unit tests, and
also add some assertions that make sure the winner list is never an
unusual size.

I also believe that #401 is ok, but I want you to do extensive testing
with many batch files, and also make some JUnit tests.

#410 is a new issue you still have to address. We should talk about it.

#408 is also a new issue that needs to be fixed and JUnit tested.

#411 is about JUnit tests on the Othello WPC. I don't think there are
currently any problems, but I want tests to make sure.

There were major issues with both heuristics and fitness functions. The
fitness functions were not properly taking into account who the current
player way, so that the value they returned was sometimes the same for
both players. Heuristic functions and minimax were incorrectly assuming
that the current player always wanted to maximize the score (I think I
steered you wrong on this) but the reality is that the first player
wants to maximize the score and the second player wants to minimize it.
This means all heuristic functions should be interpreted as indicating
how good the state is for player 1 (negative scores are good for player
2).

This update is a lot of changes. Look around and test things out. Make
sure everything works, and add lots of assertions. If you don't know why
I changed something, then ask me about it (feel free to do so
immediately in email or on GitHub so you don't forget to ask).

#390 Implemented Random Chance in Minimax Player

The Minimax Player now has a way of choosing a random legal Move as
opposed to the best possible Move. The process was based on Temporal
Difference Learning Versus Co-Evolution for Acquiring Othello Position
Evaluation by Simon Lucas and Thomas Runarsson. The default value for
this random chance is 0%, but this can be changed by altering the
minimaxRandomChance double Parameter to a value preferably between 0 and
1. The paper has been cited and linked to in the Minimax Player class.

#297 OffsetHybrID class

Created new class that extends HyperNEATCPPNGenotype and is intended to
implement one of the extensions of HybrID. This is the most complex and
overall best-performing implementation of HybrID, evolving direct and
indirect encodings simultaneously. This class has not been tested yet,
and there is a good amount of repeated code that could be generalized in
the future.

Added support for process layer width

This allows for increased receptive field depth in a convolutional
network, but in general also allows for side by side substrate
processing layers at each depth level in standard HyperNEAT networks. Of
course, many extra CPPN outputs are needed to handle all of this.

#359 Alternative approach to remixing images

Created a method that remixed images in a new way. Instead of averaging
the HSB within a given window, it read in the individual HSBs at evenly
spaced points across a window and read them in as inputs to the CPPN.
This method was interesting (could translate image/create static that
looked like pencil/brush strokes), but it didn't introduce anything
especially new/exciting and slowed down the interface a lot, so I'm
going back to the original remixing. Keeping this method around just in
case we need it in the future, though.

Fixed network display with microRTS map sequence

Addresses issues #348 .
Now the network displays at the correct size before the evaluation
happens. This was accomplished by adding a new method to the LonerTask
that is executed BEFORE the evaluation happens. This is required,
because LonerTask displays the network before it executes the evaluation
code, but in the old code, the map size change occurred inside of the
evaluation code. Now, the map change happens in the new preEval method
(from LonerTask, but overridden in MicroRTSTask).

evaluateAll method of SinglePopulationCoevolutionTask will need to call
preEval right before evaluateGroup gets called.

Fixed assertion

Assertion in NSGA 2 was comparing the wrong genotyp IDs. The assertion
was never an issue when running with assertions off, but I don't think
there was an actual error. However, it is worth noting that the genotype
returned by crossover can (will?) have the same ID as its input. This is
why it is important to copy the genotype before applying crossover,
since the copy operation does result in a new ID.

#324 Minor EndState Change to Othello

The Number of Passes is reset to 0 if a Player makes a Move. The reason
for this is to prevent the Game from ending early; if a Player passes
early in the Game, the next time either Player passes will be the

unable to make a Move.

More board game changes

The possibleBoardGameStates method should indicate which player is about
to play next, in order to be able to create all possible successor
states.

Also, it is bad practice to print things out from within a class,
because it may not always be used in the way that you happen to be using
it in your tests. It is better to have methods for accessing a String
representation if needed.

Avoid using static variables

If you are assigning a value to a static variable inside of a
constructor, you are usually doing something wrong. Avoid unnecessary
use of static variables. Instead, allow for multiple distinct instances
of a board game to exist at the same time.

#299 Sound from CPPN method

Implemented method called amplitudeGenerator() that uses a CPPN to
generate sound. CPPN takes in time, frequency, and bias and outputs
amplitude. The method generates an array of doubles that can be played
through the play method in StdAudio. The frequency was manipulated
initially using a sine function, and then using a square wave function
and triangle function from ActivationFunctions.java. The sine function
generated a wide variety of noises and graphs - quiet noises had a very
small amplitude and loud noises had larger amplitudes. The pitch was not
manipulated in the mutations, but timbre and volume displayed great
variety. A lot of very interesting images were also generated when the
functions were plotted using linePlot() in GraphicsUtil. The square wave
function had some sudden dropoffs, and the triangle functions generated
more spikes, which created a scratchy quality in many of the mutations.
Combining all three functions didn't really do much, it just made the
output extra loud in most cases. Yay!

Reduced CPPN inputs for Bottom1DSubstrateMapping too

The Bottom1DSubstrateMapping ignores the x coordinate, so CPPNs that use
it do not need CPPN inputs. Therefore, using it (with Tetris) now
reduces the number of CPPN inputs. Extending this same benefit to other
HyperNEAT tasks will need to be done on a case by case basis.

Tetris CPPNs have fewer inputs with 1D Bertsekas extractor

The 1D hand-designed features for Tetris are organized linearly, so Y
inputs are needed to the CPPN. Elimination of these unused inputs could
slightly improve HyperNEAT performance with intelligent features. #266

Added methods to HyperNEATTask

The HyperNEATTask now has methods to get the number of CPPN inputs and
to filter the "default" set of inputs containing x1,y1,x2,y2,bias. This
will allow for 1D substrates ( #266 ).

Currently, every HyperNEAT task uses the default definitions of these
methods, which correspond to 2D substrates. The next step is to modify
the HyperNEAT Tetris task to actually change the number of inputs and
filter the default input set, when appropriate.

Safety checks in TWEANN Crossover removed

TWEANN Crossover still had lots of if/else checks verifying correct
structure during the crossover process. These were remnants from when I
was doing serious testing of this code, since there used to be problems
here. In the current, working code, none of the checks should every
fail, so I either removed them entirely or switched them to assertions
as appropriate. Hopefully, this will make crossover faster.

Memory leak fixed in TWEANN Crossover

Instead of creating a new genotype inside of the crossover method, the
toReturn parameter is both modified and returned. This should not cause
any problems because the genotype sent in as a parameter here is a copy
of a genotype and not an actual member of a parent population.

I have verified with the profiler that this new approach does not cause
a memory leak, but I need to verify via other means that it does not
cause other problems. Check JUnit tests, do some short evolution runs in
several domains, etc.

Also, this test revealed that crossover is extremely slow. From looking
at the code, I think there are some ways to speed it up a little bit.

static Gene classes

I made the NodeGene and LinkGene classes static so that they are not
implicitly tied to instances of TWEANNGenotype. I think this allows
certain TWEANNGenotypes to be garbage collected that could not be
collected before, though I'm not entirely certain. This version of the
code seems functionally identical, so I'm going to keep the changes.
#254

Smaller networks with HyperNEAT seeded tasks

When a HyperNEAT task is used to seed the initial population, a boolean
is set that makes TWEANNGenotypes use a different type of NodeGene and
LinkGene. Specifically, several optional fields are not included, which
allows the size (in memory) of the networks to be smaller.

For example, in trial runs in Tetris, the size of network xml save files
drops from 38,860KB to  26,069KB. More could be done if the link weights
were switched from doubles to floats, but I fear that this could
actually affect evolution performance.

Despite this change, I might still have memory problems. A lot of my
profiling tests indicated that memory is leaking TWEANNGenotype
instances ... there are more Live instances than there should be per
generation.

Testing must continue, but having the option for smaller networks helps.

#254

There are now plain node and link genes and full node and link genes.
The plain versions involve fewer fields, and therefore take up less

Implemented getSubstrateGenotype()

This method gets the TWEANNGenotype representation of the substrate
network generated by a CPPN. This code was in the getPhenotype() method,
but was moved to this new method to allow the TWEANNGenotype rather than
the TWEANN itself, which is what the getPhenotype() method returns. In
fact, the getPhenotype() metho simply calls the new
getSubstrateGenotype() method, and then returns the phenotype from the
resulting genotype.

This change should given easy access to TWEANNGenotype methods, allowing
easier addressing of issue #246

remove the rlGluePort parameter from the code and batch files though.

NetGlue -> LocalGlue

This whole time I've been using the NetGlue codec for RL-Glue, which
sets up three separate threads which communicate using sockets. However,
it turns out this is completely unnecessary and wastefully slow. There
is a LocalGlue codec that just runs everything in a single thread
without needing any socket communication. It also does not require the
RLGlue.exe program, which means that we should be able to run this code
on non-Windows systems now.

Fixed issues with HyperNEATCPPNGenotype and SubstrateMLP

The HyperNEATCPPNGenotype was actually initializing the innovation
numbers wrong so that they were organized in column-major order rather
than row-major order. This means that inputs and connections would have
been set up in a weird way that didn't correspond to the coordinate
frame.

Additionally, the SubstrateMLP had similar but different problems. It's
links were being established correctly, but the inputs were being loaded
incorrectly. Additionally, the outputs were being extracted incorrectly.
This once again has to do with the distinction between row- and
column-major ordering.

At this point, but the TWEANNs generated by HyperNEATCPPNGenotype and
the SubstrateMLP are identical in their behavior ... at least, the
testProcess test of SubstrateMLPTest passes. The valuesTest still fails,
but I'll leave that to Lauren.

There are also pieces of commented print statements all over the place
that should be cleaned up, but that can be left for later.

MLP and SubstrateMLP

I fixed the NetworkUtilTest, but SubstrateMLP still has problems. I did
find some genuine errors, but they were small. The main issue was that
my TWEANN activates input neurons before they transmit, which is
actually NOT the standard neural network model, but should be harmless
to do. However, the SubstrateMLP was wrong because it didn't take the
quirk of my TWEANN into account. The other changes I made to Substrate
MLP were just for tidiness.

However, SubstrateMLP and TWEANNs generated by CPPNs are still not
compatible, and I know why: the structures are slightly different
because of reflections across the diagonals of the substrates. I think
the error might actually be in the HyperNEATCPPNGenotype in how it
matches up innovation numbers with nodes. They seem to count down across
columns rather than across rows. However, a simple attempt at fixing
this did not immediately solve the problem, so I reverted changes to
that class for now.

Need to look closely at both SubstrateMLP and HyperNEATCPPNGenotype. For
now, I've left some commented debugging code in certain classes.

PredPrey new experiment/parameters/batch

Created experiment for cooperative coevolution based off of the best
result from the last experiment, which was coOp multi CCQ with indiv
distance to each prey for each population-specific predator (each
population only has the distance function for that population), except
without the "quick" fitness part of it. This was done in order to more
closely follow the RRM paper that this is all based off of (distance and
caught fitness only) but with multi-objective rather than a single more
complex fitness (and with cooperative coevolution). I am also hoping
that this will cause more complex behavior (such as herding) instead of
rushing to catch the first prey then the second prey as quick as
possible.

the other populations have a size of zero.

Slight speedup of HyperNEAT in Pred/Prey

Instead of having one network controller per agent, all agents on the
same team literally share the same network (the default is to make
several copies of the network). This saves a little time in that the
phenotype is only generated once per trial, and the actual evaluation
time cuts down from 12000 to around 8000 (at the start of evolution ...
evaluation time in this domain also depends on performance)

Added the PreyMinimizeCaughtObjective and parameters to run the other two new ones

Added PreyMinimizeCaughtObjective. Now there are mirror image fitness
functions between the predators and the prey of the following based
fitness scores: total game time, number of prey caught, speed of each
prey's death, distance between the predators and the prey, and the
fitness functions implemented exactly (generalized as much as possible
to allow for variable numbers of prey and predators) from the RRM paper.
Other than these 10 fitness functions, there's just one more for the
predator called the PredatorCatchCloseObjective which is a remade
version of the RRM paper predator fitness function because I was unable
to generalize their predator fitness function (in the paper it was hard
coded for 2 prey). This remaking process was not required for the prey
RRM fitness function because it was able to be generalized.

Fixes to ImageMatch resolution

Removed large French Flag again ... we really don't need it. That's the
whole point of the CPPNs having infinite resolution. I changed the main
method of the ImageMatchTask to demonstrate this. It takes a single CPPN
and uses it to draw the same image at 3 different sizes. I also changed
how the image size and override parameters work. If the size is not
being overridden, then watching the result from ImageMatch will be the
same size as the original image. However, if the size is overridden,
then the new width and height are used by the CPPN to draw its image. It
is important to note that the CPPN was only trained to match the
original smaller image. The fact that you can rescale the image after
the face is just a cool feature of CPPNs.

Finished up the Torus PredPrey RRM paper fitness functions

Finished up the Torus PredPrey RRM paper fitness functions by creating a
static method in my predatorMinimizeDistanceFromPreyObjective which
found distance from each predator to each prey and summed those up then
found the sum of those sums (which was already being done, but was moved
to a static method) and then I was able to call this method from the RRM
predator method to implement that. Because of the equation in the paper,
the RRM predator fitness function requires that there is two prey and
throws an exception if there is not. The RRM prey fitness function
should work with any number of prey or predators

CPPN problem fixed!

The problem was the absolute value function! This is the only activation
function whose value is not restricted to a finite range. This was
causing network activations to rise to the point where they reached
infinity, and once you introduce that you get all kinds of problems like
NaN values. These NaN values made images look terrible, ruined the image
match fitness function, but also broke the "contract" of sorting
comparators, causing the exceptions with TimSort. I was able to remove
the system property to use the legacy sorting method. I found the error
by adding tons of asserts to the code. Since asserts only run when a
command line parameter is set, I'm going to go ahead and leave them in
... they were really helpful!

With this fix, the French Flag can be evolved again. The absolute value
function must have been disabled the time I initially evolved it, but I
suppose it got reactivated in a commit that someone else made.

Note: random CPPNs still produce boring black images sometimes, but this
is reasonable.
